@node "Document_0" "Introduction"
 ======================================================================

                            @{b}SciCalc V2.01
                             User Manual
                        Brian Savage (C)1997@{ub}

======================================================================

@{b}Introduction@{ub} 

SciCalc V2.01 is a full function scientific calculator for WorkBench which
mimics many of the functions & operations of popular hand held calculators.

I wrote this program back in 1994 but never did release it to Aminet.  It is
written and compiled in F-Basic.  I now use SAS/C and one of these days I'm
going to re-write SciCalc in C.

SciCalc has a Gadtools interface and requires at least Workbench 2.1+.

I hope you find it useful.
@endnode

@node "Document_1" "Installation"


@{b}Installing SciCalc@{ub}

1.  Copy SciCalc and its accompanying .guide file to the directory of your
    choice.

2.  SciCalc also comes with a custom font (scicalc).  Copy this font to your
    fonts: directory. This font IS REQUIRED.

3.  Example Arexx scripts should be copied to your REXX: directory.
@endnode

@node "Document_2" "Features"


@{b}@{u}Features@{ub}@{uu}

1.  9 @{"constantĀregisters" link "Document_10" 0};

2.  mouse or @{"keyboard" link "Document_4" 0} operation;

3.  @{"trigonometric" link "Document_9" 0} functions;

4.  @{"mathemetical" link "Document_12" 0} functions

5.  respects '@{"OrderĀofĀOperations" link "Document_13" 0}' -> Algebraic logic system

6.  16 levels of @{"parenthesis" link "Document_13" 0}

7.  @{"floatingĀmemory" link "Document_10" 0};

8.  @{"ClipBoard" link "Document_3" 0} support - unit 0;

9.  @{"PublicĀScreen" link "Document_5" 0} support - jump between any open public screen;

10. @{"ArexxĀsupport" link "Document_6" 0} - add your own functions via Arexx (up to 9) or pass
    values back and forth between Scicalc and other Arexx equipped
    applications.
@endnode

@node "Document_3" "ClipBoard"


@{b}ClipBoard@{ub}

Send values back and forth between SciCalc and ClipBoard using the following
submenus.

1.  'Copy' currently displayed value to clipboard (Right-Amiga C)

2.  'Paste' value from clipboard to SciCalc. SciCalc performs error
    checking on the value obtained before pasting into the
    SciCalc display. If the value is not a number, ie
    9.999999E-99>|x|>9.999999E99 an error will occur.
    This error will also occur if the value contains non numeric text
    (with the exception of characters used in scientific format)
    or if non displayable characters such as line feeds, carriage
    returns etc are present. (Right-Amiga V)
@endnode

@node "Document_4" "keyboard"


@{b}Keyboard Equivalents@{ub}

Underlined characters denote keyboard equivalents for most 'keys' except for
the following:

    Key                 Keyboard Equivalent
    ===                 ===================

    'AC'                Escape

    'EXE'               RETURN or ENTER

    numeric keys 0-9    corresponding keyboard (or keypad)
                        numeric keys.

    +,-,/,*,(,),.       corresponding keyboard (or keypad) keys
@endnode

@node "Document_5" "Public Screen"


@{b}Public Screen@{ub}

Presents user with requester which will display all public screens currently
available. After selecting one of the screens presented, the SciCalc window
will close and then reopen on the screen that was selected (Right Amiga S).
@endnode

@node "Document_6" "Arexx support"


@{b}Arexx Support@{ub}

Arexx support has been added for version 2.0 which allows the user to add
custom functions or to pass values between SciCalc and Arexx equipped
applications.

SciCalc's Arexx port is named "SC_REXX". If more than one copy of SciCalc is
running, or if another application has an Arexx port of the same name then
SciCalc's Arexx port is named "SC_REXX1".

The default file extension for SciCalc Arexx scripts is ".scrx".

Arexx scripts are executed synchronously (ie SciCalc will wait until the
Arexx script returns before executing the next keystroke).

SciCalc currently has 4 Arexx commands. These commands are not case
sensitive. They are as follows:


GETVAL ->       gets the currently displayed value from SciCalc and returns
                it in the Arexx RESULT variable.

GETREG <n>  ->  gets the value currently stored in SciCalc constant
                register 'n' (where n can range from 1 to 9) and
                returns it in the Arexx RESULT variable.

PUTVAL <x>  ->  sends value 'x' to SciCalc where it is displayed.
                'x' can be any real number or integer.
                (9.999999E-99<=|x|<=9.999999E99)

PUTREG <n> <x> -> sends value 'x' to SciCalc and stores it in constant
                register 'n' where 'n' can range from 1 to 9.
                'x' can be any real number or integer.
                (9.999999E-99<=|x|<=9.999999E99)


Arexx scripts can be attached to any of the 9 numeric keys (1 through 9
inclusive). Scripts are attached by adding a tooltype of the form:

"REXX<n>=<arexx script filename> <optional display characters>"

<n> is an integer from 1 to 9 corresponding to numeric keys 1 to 9.

<arexx script filename> is the full path & filename of the Arexx script

<optional display characters> are up to 4 characters which can be displayed
above the numeric key.


Example:

To attach the Arexx script "CtoF.scrx" with display characters "C->F" to
key#5, the tooltype would be:

"REXX5=REXX:CTOF C->F"

Note the full path name for the Arexx script, the file extension is not
required if ".scrx" is used, and the space delimiting the filename from the
display character. If you have assigned REXX: to dh0:rexx (for example)

9 example Arexx scripts have been included. They are:

1.  ctof.scrx            -> Celsius to Fahrenheit temperature conversion 

2.  factorial.scrx       -> Factorial function 

3.  ftoc.scrx            -> Fahrenheit to Celsius temperature conversion 

4.  milespergallon.scrx  -> obtains miles/gallon (Imperial) when given
                            litre & kilometres (Canadian users)  

5.  polar_to_rect.scrx   -> converts polar to rectangular coords

6.  polynomial.scrx      -> calculates value of polynomial  

7.  FinalCalctoSC.scrx     -> takes value from current cell of FinalCalc
                            and displays it on SciCalc display  

8.  rect_to_polar.scrx   -> rectangular to polar coords conversion

9.  SCtoFinalCalc.scrx   -> takes value from SciCalc display and puts it
                            in current FinalCalc cell


@{u}Arexx Error Messages@{uu} 

When an error occurs during the execution of an Arexx script, SciCalc
displays the following error message:

    "AREXX ERROR n"

where 'n' is the error type as defined in Appendix A of the Arexx User's
Reference Manual (1<=n<=48) or a SciCalc Error where 'n' is defined as
follows:

    n=50 Unknown Arexx command

    n=51 Argument supplied (integer) is outside the
         range of possible choices

    n=52 Value supplied is not a number

    n=54 Required integer argument is not an integer

To clear the display select [AC].


@{u}Arexx Return Codes@{uu} 

Return codes may be returned to SciCalc to alert the user of a certain
condition (ie RETURN 20). SciCalc interprets return codes like errors but to
avoid confusion with Arexx error codes, the message is displayed as follows:

    "AREXX RET n"

where 'n' is the return code.

Do not use RETURN or EXIT to return values to SciCalc because SciCalc
interprets these return codes as errors as stated above. Only use the PUTVAL
or PUTREG commands to return values to SciCalc.

To clear the display select [AC].
@endnode

@node "Document_7" "Tool Types"


@{b}ToolTypes@{ub}

When started from the WorkBench OR CLI/Shell, the following tooltype
arguments may be passed to SciCalc:

1.  TOPX / TOPY

    These tooltypes define the x & y coordinates of the top left hand
    corner of the SciCalc window. To define a location on the screen
    where you would like SciCalc to open, these tooltypes are used as
    follows:

        To open SciCalc 100 pixels from the left hand side
        of the screen and 20 pixels down from the top of
        the screen;

                       TOPX=100
                       TOPY=20

        Error checking is performed on these values to prevent
        SciCalc from opening a window outside of the screen
        boundary.


2.  REXX<n>

    To attach an Arexx script to a numeric key (see @{"Arexx" link "Document_6" 0} section below).

    Note: When using SciCalc from the CLI/Shell ensure that SciCalc.info is
    in the same directory as SciCalc in order to obtain the tooltypes.
@endnode

@node "Document_8" "Functions"


@{b}Function Description@{ub}


SciCalc functions are organized into the following groups:

@{"Trigonometric" link "Document_9" 0}

@{"Memory" link "Document_10" 0}

@{"Math" link "Document_12" 0}

@{"Arithmetic" link "Document_13" 0} 

@{"Miscellaneous" link "Document_14" 0}


@{u}Note:@{uu}

The functions shall be described and followed by the sequence of keystrokes
required to use the function. Keys denoted by "[ ]" refer to the functions
displayed ON the keys, while "{ }" refers to inscriptions above the keys.
@endnode

@node "Document_9" "Trigonometric"


@{b}TRIGONOMETRIC FUNCTIONS@{ub}


1.    PI  - Displays the value of PI using the formula
      (ATN(1/2)+ATN(1/3))*4

      KEYSTROKES: [INV]{PI}

2.    Sine function

      KEYSTROKES: [SIN]

      Example: Find the Sine of 30 degrees. Enter the following
      keystrokes: [3][0][SIN][EXE]; which shall display the following:
      0.5 (display in degrees)


3.    Arc-sine (x) where  -1 >= x <= 1

      KEYSTROKES: [INV]{ASN}

      Example: Find the Arc Sine of 0.7071. Enter the following
      keystrokes: [.][7][0][7][1][INV]{ASN}[=]; which shall display the
      following: 44.99945 (display in degrees)

4.    Cosine function

      KEYSTROKES: [COS]

      Example: Similar to Sine Example

5.    Arc-cosine (x) where  -1 >= x <= 1

      KEYSTROKES: [INV]{ACS}

      Example: Similar to Arc Sine example

6.    Tangent function

      KEYSTROKES: [TAN]

      Example: Similar to Sine Example

7.    Arc-tangent

      KEYSTROKES: [INV]{ATN}

      Example: Similar to Arc Sine example

8.    Hyperbolic Sine (Sinh)

      KEYSTROKES: [HYP][SIN]

      Example: Find the hyperbolic sine of 45 degrees. Enter
      [4][5][HYP][SIN][EXE] which displays the following: 1.746713E38

9.   Hyperbolic Arc Sine (Arcsinh) where -10e50 < x < -10e-50

      KEYSTROKES: [INV][HYP]{ASN}  KEYS: (1)(8)(15)

      Example: Find Arcsinh of 10 degrees. Enter
      [1][0][INV][HYP]{ASN}[EXE] which displays the following:
      2.998223

10.   Hyperbolic Cosine

      KEYSTROKES: [HYP][COS]

      Example: Similar to Sinh example

11.   Hyperbolic Arc Cosine (Arccosh) where 1 <= x < 10e50

      KEYSTROKES: [INV][HYP]{ACS}

      Example: Similar to Arcsinh example

12.   Hyperbolic Tangent (Tanh)

      KEYSTROKES: [HYP][TAN]

      Example: Similar to Sinh example

13.   Hyperbolic Arc Tangent (Arctanh) where -1 < x < 1

      KEYSTROKES: [INV][HYP]{ATN}

      Example: Similar to ArcSinh example
@endnode

@node "Document_10" "Memory"


@{b}MEMORY FUNCTIONS@{ub}

SciCalc V2.0 has 9 Constant registers referenced by each of the numeric keys
(1 to 9) as well as 1 Floating Memory register.


@{u}Constant Registers 1 - 9@{uu}

14.   [ K ][ n ] - Constant Memory Register Recall Key - Displays the value
      currently stored in constant register 'n', where n is one of the
      numeric keys 1 to 9.


15.   [INV]{ Kin }[ n ] - Constant Memory Store Key; Places the currently
      displayed value into Constant register 'n', where n is one of the
      numeric keys 1 to 9.


@{u}Floating Memory@{uu}

16.   "M+" - Memory Add; adds the value of the currently displayed value
      to the value currently stored in the floating memory register.

      KEYSTROKES: [ M+ ]

17.   "M-" - Memory Subtract; subtracts the value of the currently
      displayed value from the value currently stored in the floating
      memory register.

      KEYSTROKES: [INV]{ M- }

32.   "MR" - Memory Recall Key; displays the value currently stored in the
      floating memory register.

      KEYSTROKES: [ MR ]

33.   "CM" - Memory Clear; Resets the value in the floating memory
      register to zero.

      KEYSTROKES: [INV]{CM}
@endnode

@node "Document_12" "Math"


@{b}MATH FUNCTIONS@{ub}


35.   "SQR" - Square root function.

      KEYSTROKE: [INV]{ SQR } -> note symbol different from symbol actually
                                 displayed.

36.   "X^2"  - Square function.

      KEYSTROKES: [INV]{ X^2 } ->note symbol different from symbol
                                 actually displayed.

37.   "1/X"  - Reciprocal function

      KEYSTROKES: [INV]{ 1/X }

38.   "y^x"  - Power function

      KEYSTROKES: 'y'[INV]{ Y^X }'x' [EXE]

      Example: Find the value of 2^3. Enter [2][INV]{ Y^X }[3][EXE] which
      displays '8'.

43.   "LN"   - Natural logarithm function (base e)

      KEYSTROKES: 'x'[INV]{ lnX }

44.   "EXP"  - Exponential function (e^x)

      KEYSTROKES: [INV]{ EXP } -> note symbol different from symbol
                                  actually displayed.

45.   "LOG"  - Common logarithm function (base 10)

      KEYSTROKES: 'x'[LOG]
@endnode

@node "Document_13" "Arithmatic"


@{b}ARITHMETIC FUNCTIONS@{ub}

Equations are entered into SciCalc V2.0 the way they are written; from left
to right. Calculations are performed in accordance with the following 'Order
of Operations';

   a. Functions such as Sine, x^2, and lnX

   b. Multiplication and division

   c. Addition and subtraction

SciCalc's algebraic logic system eliminates the need to use parentheses in
many cases. Consider the following simple example:

    2+3*8= ?

Keeping in mind that multiplication is performed before addition, SciCalc
performs the calculation as follows:

    2+(3*8)=26   -> without the use of parentheses.


However when parenthesis are required, up to 16 levels can be used and up to
16 pending operations.

46.   "+"    - Addition

47.   "-"    - Subtraction

48.   "*"    - Multiplication

49.   "/"    - Division

50.   "()" - Parentheses (up to 16 levels). Note; a closed bracket
      without a corresponding open bracket will result in an 'Error'
      message.

      KEYSTROKE: [(] and [)]
@endnode

@node "Document_14" "Miscellaneous"


@{b}MISCELLANEOUS FUNCTIONS@{ub}

51.   "AC"  - All Clear; clears display and all pending operations.
      "AC" must be pressed to clear an 'Error' message.

      KEYSTROKE: [AC]

52.   "EE"  - Exponent function.

      KEYSTROKE: [EE]

      Example: Display 1.25e-4. Enter '1.25'[EE]'4'[+/-]


54.   "X-Y" - X Exchange Y; Switches the value of x and y where 'y' is
      a pending operation.

      Example: [1][/][2][=] 0.5; [2][/][1][X-Y][=] 0.5

55.   "ANS" - Last Answer; Displays value of preceding calculation.

      KEYSTROKES: [ANS]
@endnode

@node "Document_15" "Menus"


@{b}Menu Options@{ub}

(Note - keyboard equivalents in brackets)

1. Angular Measure

   Mutually exclusive submenu options to select angular measurement in:

   1.  'Degrees' (Right Amiga D);
   2.  'Radians' (Right Amiga R); or
   3.  'Gradians' (Right Amiga G).


2. @{"ClipBoard" link "Document_3" 0}

3. @{"PublicĀScreen" link "Document_5" 0}


4. About

   Presents the user with a requester containing information about SciCalc.


5. Quit

   Quits SciCalc (Right Amiga Q).
@endnode

@node "Document_16" "Error Messages"


@{b}Error Messages@{ub}

When the an error occurs during execution of an operation SciCalc displays
the following error message:

    "ERROR - n"

The error type 'n' is defined as:

        1.  division by zero  
        2.  overflow/out of range  
        3.  mismatched brackets  
        4.  square root negative number  
        5.  clipboard error - unrecognizable data

To clear the display select [AC].

Arexx error messages are discussed in the @{"Arexx" link "Document_6" 87} section.
@endnode

